    "summary": "\"Experience\" as main, \"empirical\" only when disambiguating from 体验",
    "content": "**\"Experience\"** as the main translation, with \"empirical\" added only when disambiguation is needed.\n\nThe reason is simple: 经验 rarely appears as a standalone noun in these essays. It almost always appears in compound phrases — \"经验的总结\" (summary of experience), \"经验的预测\" (prediction from experience), \"经验性的\" (empirical). In these compounds, the context already signals the empirical/accumulated sense without needing the qualifier. And \"经验性的\" naturally translates as \"empirical\" on its own — you wouldn't say \"empirical-experiential.\"\n\nThe disambiguation problem between 经验 and 体验 is real but localized. The two terms almost never appear in the same sentence or paragraph. When they do co-occur (rare), the translator can add \"empirical\" at that point. Making \"empirical experience\" the default would mean writing it dozens of times where context already makes the meaning clear, just to handle a collision that occurs perhaps twice across all eight essays.\n\nDictionary entry should read: **经验 → \"experience\" (main); \"empirical experience\" (when distinguishing from 体验)**"
  }
}
